Classification Project - Hotel Booking Cancellation Prediction

Objective

The increasing number of cancellations calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in predicting which booking is likely to be canceled. INN Hotels Group has a chain of hotels in Portugal, they are facing problems with the high number of booking cancellations and have reached out to your firm for data-driven solutions. Here, we are going to analyze the data provided to find which factors have a high influence on booking cancellations, build a predictive model that can predict which booking is going to be canceled in advance, and help in formulating profitable policies for cancellations and refunds.

Data Dictionary

  • Booking_ID: The unique identifier of each booking

  • no_of_adults: The number of adults

  • no_of_children: The number of children

  • no_of_weekend_nights: The number of weekend nights (Saturday and Sunday) the guest stayed or booked to stay at the hotel

  • no_of_week_nights: The number of weeknights (Monday to Friday) the guest stayed or booked to stay at the hotel

  • type_of_meal_plan: The type of meal plan booked by the customer: Not Selected (No meal plan selected). Meal Plan 1 (Breakfast). Meal Plan 2 (Half board - breakfast and one other meal). Meal Plan 3 (Full board - breakfast, lunch, and dinner)

  • required_car_parking_space: Does the customer require a car parking space? (0 - No, 1- Yes)

  • room_type_reserved: The type of room reserved by the customer. The values are ciphered (encoded) by INN Hotels.

  • lead_time: The number of days between the date of booking and the arrival date

  • arrival_year: The year of arrival date

  • arrival_month: The month of arrival date

  • arrival_date: The date of the month

  • market_segment_type: Market segment designation.

  • repeated_guest: Is the customer a repeated guest? (0 - No, 1- Yes)

  • no_of_previous_cancellations: The number of previous bookings that were canceled by the customer before the current booking

  • no_of_previous_bookings_not_canceled: The number of previous bookings not canceled by the customer before the current booking

  • avg_price_per_room: The average price per day for the reservation; prices of the rooms are dynamic. (in euros)

  • no_of_special_requests: The total number of special requests made by the customer (e.g. high floor, view from the room, etc.)

  • booking_status: Flag indicating if the booking was canceled or not. The class 0 represents the Not_Canceled whereas class 1 represents the Canceled label.

Observations:

  • The majority of bookings are made for 2 adults with no children. Very few bookings are made with 1 to 3 children. There are some observations with 9 and 10 children, which seems very unusual for a hotel room.

  • 70% of the times bookings are made for up to 3 week days, with some very few stays for over 10 days. Similarly, the majority of bookings does not contain any weekend night or up to 2 weekend nights.

  • 76% of the guests choose for the Meal Plan 1, which is Breakfast only. ~78% of the guests choose the Room_Type 1, which might be the most standard room.

  • We can see an upper trend on the bookings for the months of August, September, and October. For the market segment type 63% of bookings are made online, 29% offline, and 5% are corporate bookings. The remaining few ones are complementary and aviation segments.

  • 50% of the bookings does not make any special requests, and 30% will make 1 special request.

  • For our target variable, We can see that 67% of the bookings were not cancelled and 33% were cancelled. So we can say that the data is not perfectly balanced.

Model Building

Data preparation for modeling

In[]:

Random Forest Model

The random forest classifier has the benefit of presenting a better generalization and improved accuracy when compared to the decision tree classifier as it combines multiple decision trees through ensemble learning. However, random forests can be less interpretable, require more computation, and can be slower to train and predict compared to a single decision trree.

In[]:
#Creating the Random Forest Model

train_scores = []

test_scores = []

for depth in range(1, 25):

    rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state = 42, criterion = 'entropy', max_depth = depth, n_estimators = 25)

    rf = rf.fit(X_train, y_train)

    train_scores.append(1 - rf.score(X_train, y_train))

    test_scores.append(1 - rf.score(X_test, y_test))

plt.plot(range(1, 25), train_scores, '-o', label = "train")

plt.plot(range(1, 25), test_scores, '-o', label = "test")

plt.legend(loc = 'upper right')

plt.xlabel('max depth')

plt.ylim(0, 0.4)

plt.ylabel('misclassification error (pcnt)')

plt.title(f"Random Forest with 25 estimators")

fig = plt.gcf()

fig.set_size_inches(10, 6)

plt.show()
  • We can see that after as we increase the model tends to overfit and the test error does not change much. Let's try creating a random forest model with max_depth = 20 to see if we can minimize the test error.

Conclusions and Recommendations

The analysis demonstrates that machine learning can effectively predict hotel booking cancellations and guide targeted operational policies. The base Random Forest model achieved the strongest overall performance, with an accuracy of 90%, an F1 score of 84% for canceled bookings, and balanced precision-recall for non-canceled bookings (precision 91%, recall 94%). Although the tuned Random Forest reduced false negatives slightly (567 vs 675), it increased false positives significantly (800 vs 456), making the base model more reliable for day-to-day decision-making.

Business Recommendations:

  • Prioritize high-risk bookings: Since the model occasionally underestimates cancellations (81% recall for canceled bookings), the hotel should focus additional confirmation efforts on bookings flagged as potential risk; especially those with long lead times, multiple special requests, and online origin.

  • Refund and cancellation policies: With false negatives representing lost revenue from unanticipated cancellations, stricter refund rules for high-risk groups (online bookings, high room price, special requests) can reduce financial exposure. Clearly communicating these policies during booking will protect guest trust.

  • Resource allocation: The models strong recall for non-cancellations (94%) ensures most staying guests are correctly identified. This enables better staffing, housekeeping, and inventory planning, reducing wasted resources.

  • Seasonal strategy: Given peak cancellations from June to October, use the models predictions to overbook strategically or adjust marketing campaigns, while during low cancellations period (December to January), shift focus to maximizing guest experience with adequate staffing.

  • Customer engagement: Post-booking outreach should be prioritized for customers predicted as likely to cancel to either confirm intent or release rooms sooner for resale.

  • Loyalty and retention: Since repeat guests show lower cancellation rates, pairing the models predictions with a loyalty program will further reduce cancellations and marketing spend.

By integrating the Random Forest model into operations, the hotel can minimize financial losses from cancellations, optimize resource management, and implement targeted policies that enhance profitability while maintaining guest satisfaction.
